{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643034"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:48:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:48:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17978"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17978"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73082"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10692"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17978"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58553"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"11220"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24898"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24902"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73082"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is typically done by Phase 1 reactions in drug metabolism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Detoxify the substance","Convert a toxin to an innocuous substance","Activate a prodrug into a pharmacologically active metabolite","Increase the solubility of a compound","Add a chemically reactive group, permitting conjugation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPhase 1 reactions in drug metabolism primarily involve the addition of a chemically reactive group, permitting conjugation. These reactions often include oxidation, reduction, or hydrolysis, which introduce or expose functional groups on the drug molecule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetoxify the substance\u003C/strong\u003E - While Phase 1 reactions can sometimes reduce toxicity, their main role is to prepare the drug for Phase 2 reactions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConvert a toxin to an innocuous substance\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not the primary function of Phase 1 reactions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivate a prodrug into a pharmacologically active metabolite\u003C/strong\u003E - This can occur, but it is not the typical role of Phase 1 reactions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease the solubility of a compound\u003C/strong\u003E - Phase 1 reactions do not significantly increase solubility; this is more characteristic of Phase 2 reactions\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhase 1 reactions are essential for the initial modification of drugs, setting the stage for further processing in Phase 2 reactions, which often involve conjugation to increase solubility and facilitate excretion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Phase 1 reactions in drug metabolism introduce or expose functional groups on the drug molecule.","These reactions often involve oxidation, reduction, or hydrolysis processes.","Phase 1 reactions prepare drugs for further modification in Phase 2 reactions."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Omiecinski CJ, Vanden Heuvel JP, Perdew GH, Peters JM. Xenobiotic metabolism, disposition, and regulation by receptors: from biochemical phenomenon to predictors of major toxicities. Toxicol Sci. 2011 Mar;120 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S49-75. doi: 10.1093/toxsci/kfq338. Epub 2010 Nov 8. PMID: 21059794; PMCID: PMC3145385"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58553"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17978"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58553","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58553"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T00:50:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T00:50:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10692"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73082"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type"